The husband bolts upright: "How long have you been standing there?!"

"Since you started playing the hand game. Can I play too? I'm really good at rock!"

The wife sighs: "Sweetie, it's 2 AM. You need to go back to your own bed."

"But the monsters are in my room!"

The husband, now fully awake: "Okay, what do these monsters look like?"

"They look like the pile of laundry on my chair, but scarier."

The wife starts laughing: "Honey, I've been meaning to fold that laundry for three days. Even I'm scared of it at this point."

The toddler climbs into bed between them: "See? That's why I need to sleep here. To protect you from the laundry monsters."

And that's how two adults ended up sleeping on the very edge of their king-size bed while a 30-pound human starfished in the middle, somehow taking up 90% of the space.

A comedian walks on stage and says, "I'm going to tell you a joke about meta-jokes."

The audience waits.

"That was it," he says. "The joke was that I said I was going to tell you a meta-joke, but instead I just told you I was going to tell you one, which makes this statement itself the meta-joke I promised. But now that I've explained it, I've ruined it, which is also very meta. And pointing out that explaining it ruined it is even MORE meta. Should I stop? The fact that I'm asking whether I should stop is—"

Someone in the audience yells, "STOP!"

The comedian grins. "Perfect timing! You just became part of the meta-joke by breaking the fourth wall to end my infinite regression. We're all complicit now. This whole thing is performance art disguised as comedy disguised as a lecture about comedy. Take a bow, everyone—you're all comedians tonight!"

The audience applauds, unsure if they're clapping for the joke, for themselves, or for the absurdity of applauding a non-joke that became a joke by not being one.
instance_metrics.prompt: Tell me a joke about meta-jokes

instance_metrics.response:
A meta-joke and a regular joke are sitting at a coffee shop.

The regular joke says, "Why did the chicken cross the road? To get to the other side!"

The meta-joke rolls its eyes and says, "Oh please, that's so predictable. Watch this: Why did the meta-joke cross the road?"

"I don't know, why?"

"To subvert your expectations about road-crossing jokes while simultaneously acknowledging that by doing so, it has become exactly the kind of pretentious humor it was trying to critique."

The regular joke stares blankly. "I... don't get it."

The meta-joke sighs. "That's the point. The fact that you don't get it IS the joke. But now that I've explained that not getting it is the joke, you DO get it, which means it's no longer funny, which makes it funny again because—"

"STOP," interrupts the regular joke. "You know what? At least when I bomb, people know I bombed. When you bomb, you just claim it was intentional and call it 'deconstructive comedy.'"

The meta-joke pauses, then starts laughing. "Oh my god, you're right. I just got roasted by a chicken-crossing-the-road joke. That's so beautifully ironic that it's... wait, is THIS the real meta-joke?"

They both sit in confused silence, wondering if they've just become part of someone else's joke about jokes about jokes.
instance_metrics.prompt: Tell me a joke about meta-jokes

instance_metrics.response:
A meta-joke walks into a comedy club and approaches the microphone.

"Good evening, everyone! I'm here to tell you a joke about jokes that are about jokes. But first, let me acknowledge that starting with 'Good evening' is a tired comedy cliche, which I'm now pointing out, making this observation itself a meta-commentary on comedy conventions."

The audience shifts uncomfortably.

"I can see you're confused. That's perfect! Your confusion is actually the setup. See, most jokes have a setup and a punchline, but I'm a meta-joke, so MY setup is explaining that I'm explaining my setup. And the punchline? Well, the punchline is that there is no punchline—except for the fact that saying there's no punchline IS the punchline."

Someone in the back shouts, "This isn't funny!"

The meta-joke grins. "EXACTLY! You just delivered my punchline for me! The real joke was that I tricked you into participating in a joke about jokes not being funny, which made it funny, but only because it wasn't supposed to be funny, which makes it... wait, am I having an existential crisis or is this still part of the bit?"

The audience starts laughing despite themselves.

"Oh no," the meta-joke realizes, "you're laughing at my existential crisis, which means I accidentally became a regular joke while trying to be a meta-joke. I've failed so successfully that I've succeeded, which is the most meta thing of all."

*mic drop*

*picks up mic*

"Sorry, dropping the mic was too obvious. A real meta-joke would subvert that expectation by... oh god, I'm doing it again."
